00:04:45.510 --> 00:04:47.340
Anyway, as for how
this language worked,

00:04:47.340 --> 00:04:49.357
I need to take a sidetrack
and introduce you

00:04:49.357 --> 00:04:50.440
to a little bit of Arabic.

00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:52.606
I'm sure there are some
people here who know Arabic,

00:04:52.606 --> 00:04:55.300
but for those that don't, I took
a year of Arabic at UC Berkeley

00:04:55.300 --> 00:04:56.810
and absolutely fell in
love with the language.

00:04:56.810 --> 00:04:58.020
It's a wonderful language.

00:04:58.020 --> 00:05:00.020
I never imagined a language
that, grammatically,

00:05:00.020 --> 00:05:01.880
could work in that way.

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:04.780
And one of the unique
features of Arabic

00:05:04.780 --> 00:05:07.279
is that it has something
called a root system,

00:05:07.279 --> 00:05:09.070
usually a triconsonantal
root system, where

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:12.420
you have something like these
three consonants-- K, T, and B.

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:15.660
And by the way, Arabic is
written from right to left.

00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:17.900
So notice how each
consonant matches up

00:05:17.900 --> 00:05:19.900
with the orthographic
form there.

00:05:19.900 --> 00:05:23.580
And what happens is that
this root has something

00:05:23.580 --> 00:05:27.855
to do with books and writing.

00:05:27.855 --> 00:05:33.740
But the way that
it is transformed

00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:36.670
into words in the language
is that you actually arrange

00:05:36.670 --> 00:05:39.770
vowels inside and without
these consonants, and also

00:05:39.770 --> 00:05:44.320
suffixes and prefixes, to
form different types of words.

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.910
And the only thing
that remains constant

00:05:46.910 --> 00:05:50.290
is the linear order of
these three consonants.

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:54.420
So for example, these are all
verbs in different tenses.

00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:57.310
At the top, we have "naktub,"
which means "we write."

00:05:57.310 --> 00:06:01.620
Then on the lower left, we have
"aktub," which means "I write."

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:04.364
And then in the past, "katabat,"
which means "she wrote."

00:06:04.364 --> 00:06:06.530
And notice that the only
thing that's happening here

00:06:06.530 --> 00:06:09.030
is K, T, and B are always
in the exact same order.

00:06:09.030 --> 00:06:10.300
Sometimes, they're right
next to each other.

00:06:10.300 --> 00:06:11.936
Sometimes, there are
vowels in between.

00:06:11.936 --> 00:06:13.310
And you can make
even more words.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:17.000
So for example, "kaatib,"
"writer." "Maktab," "office."

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.020
And "kitaab," "book,"
just like that.

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:23.151
So I thought that was a really,
really cool way for a language

00:06:23.151 --> 00:06:23.650
to work.

00:06:23.650 --> 00:06:25.420
And I never heard of it before.

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:27.600
And so basically,
when I was creating

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:31.140
my own language, Megdevi,
I just copied it wholesale.

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:32.970
And I also created
this terrible font,

00:06:32.970 --> 00:06:34.680
which I included
just so that you

00:06:34.680 --> 00:06:36.930
could see how terrible it is.

00:06:36.930 --> 00:06:38.951
Actually, when you're
standing that far back,

00:06:38.951 --> 00:06:40.450
it actually looks
better than it is.

00:06:40.450 --> 00:06:42.860
But there are just so
many little shaky lines

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:44.290
and everything, just god awful.

00:06:44.290 --> 00:06:47.720
Anyway, so that you could
have a root like this-- ja,

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:49.850
su, fe-- and have
jaesif-- these are

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:51.940
real words from the
language-- "flame thrower."

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:54.290
Jisfe, "flame-colored."

00:06:54.290 --> 00:06:57.330
And jasif, "flame," like that.

00:07:00.196 --> 00:07:02.360
Hm, flame thrower, whatever.

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:04.450
And you can also see that
with the writing system,

00:07:04.450 --> 00:07:06.750
I was heavily
inspired by Arabic.

00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:08.292
So if you were to
spell something

00:07:08.292 --> 00:07:10.500
that would be roughly
equivalent to the pronunciation

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:14.440
of "writer" in Arabic, "kaatib,"
it would look like this.

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:18.070
And so you can see the K,
it's got that thing on it.

00:07:18.070 --> 00:07:20.780
And it just has a little
bubble on the top.

00:07:20.780 --> 00:07:23.024
And the B has one dot
except it's above.

00:07:23.024 --> 00:07:24.440
And there's another
little bubble.

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:27.280
And the T looks more T-like.

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:30.570
It was clearly just derivative.

00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:32.940
The worst part about it
though, was, in my mind,

00:07:32.940 --> 00:07:36.250
the way that I
understood language

00:07:36.250 --> 00:07:38.800
to work, and specifically,
how I created words

00:07:38.800 --> 00:07:39.550
for this language.

00:07:39.550 --> 00:07:41.600
So grammatically,
it's a neat system.

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:45.200
But I just want you to look
at some of these [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:47.330
In order to be able
to appreciate this,

00:07:47.330 --> 00:07:50.930
you have to know these
three patterns right here.

00:07:50.930 --> 00:07:54.250
So the 1, 2, and 3 are for the
consonants that will change

00:07:54.250 --> 00:07:55.170
root to root.

00:07:55.170 --> 00:07:57.150
And then pay attention
to the vowels on top.

00:07:57.150 --> 00:08:00.210
If it has an "ae" as the
first vowel and an "i"

00:08:00.210 --> 00:08:03.140
as the second vowel, that's
more or less a thing.

00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:06.720
If it has an "ay" as the first
vowel and an "i" as the second,

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:07.920
that's a person.

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:11.115
And then if it has an
"ee" as the first vowel

00:08:11.115 --> 00:08:13.960
and "eh" as the second
vowel, that is a place.

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:17.590
All right, so our
first word, there

00:08:17.590 --> 00:08:21.810
wasn't a place one for it,
but "jaelif" is a sailboat,

00:08:21.810 --> 00:08:23.850
"jelif" is "sailor."

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:25.210
All right, fine.

00:08:25.210 --> 00:08:26.510
That makes more or less sense.

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:30.480
Next, W, V, D.
"Wived" is "marina.

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:32.210
"Wevid" is "mariner."

00:08:32.210 --> 00:08:35.549
And what the difference is
between "sailor" and "mariner,"

00:08:35.549 --> 00:08:37.071
hm, I'm not sure there.

00:08:37.071 --> 00:08:38.820
We know what the
difference is in English.

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:40.620
Basically, they came from
two different languages,

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:41.786
and that's why we have them.

00:08:41.786 --> 00:08:44.590
But yeah, so now we have both
of these words in this language.

00:08:44.590 --> 00:08:47.170
So I'm like, all right,
all right, fine, whatever.

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:50.320
Then we have "thaenis," which
was vessel, specifically,

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:52.270
an aquatic vessel.

00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:54.390
So now we have a word for
"sailboat" and "vessel."

00:08:54.390 --> 00:08:56.660
And "thenis,"
which is "captain."

00:08:56.660 --> 00:08:59.516
Next, "boat," which is
different from "sailboat," which

00:08:59.516 --> 00:09:00.640
is different from "vessel."

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:01.740
That was "chaesich."

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:04.050
And we also have "chisich,"
"boathouse," which

00:09:04.050 --> 00:09:05.500
is different from "marina."

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:08.134
And "chesich," "boater," which
is different from "sailor,"

00:09:08.134 --> 00:09:09.800
which is different
from "captain," which

00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:13.060
is different from "mariner."

00:09:13.060 --> 00:09:15.030
Then it goes even further.

00:09:15.030 --> 00:09:18.270
We have a very special root
that's just for clipper ships,

00:09:18.270 --> 00:09:19.440
"baelil."

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:22.766
Presumably, "belil"
is somebody who sails

00:09:22.766 --> 00:09:24.650
a clipper ship or something.

00:09:24.650 --> 00:09:26.470
But I think that the
reason that we even

00:09:26.470 --> 00:09:28.730
have this word for clipper
ship is just because I

00:09:28.730 --> 00:09:31.370
was a fan of the Clippers.

00:09:31.370 --> 00:09:32.940
And so why not?

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:35.110
I wonder, actually, if that
B-L-L root has something

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:36.430
to do with the Clippers.

00:09:36.430 --> 00:09:39.790
All I'm thinking
of is Bison Dele.

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:41.330
Somebody remember him?

00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:43.350
Anybody remember
his original name?

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:44.740
Because I literally don't.

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:46.100
All right, anyway, moving on.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:48.540
Anyway, so there are a
bunch of other crazy things

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:49.740
about this language.

00:09:49.740 --> 00:09:51.630
For example, I had
taken Esperanto.

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:54.926
So the case system for
this language was identical

00:09:54.926 --> 00:09:55.550
to Esperanto's.

00:09:58.770 --> 00:09:59.820
The number suffixes.

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:02.840
So looking at number systems
for natural languages

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:04.320
is a fascinating thing.

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:07.080
But this language literally
had separate suffixes

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:12.450
for number words that were in
the tens, hundreds, thousands,

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:15.720
hundred thousands, millions,
billions, trillions,

00:10:15.720 --> 00:10:17.370
up to the quadrillions.

00:10:17.370 --> 00:10:21.630
So that you could take
the root for 1 and make 1,

00:10:21.630 --> 00:10:25.010
10, 100, 1,000, 10,000,
so on, all the way up

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:27.829
to 1 quadrillion.

00:10:27.829 --> 00:10:29.870
I don't think that there
are other languages that

00:10:29.870 --> 00:10:31.740
do things like that.

00:10:31.740 --> 00:10:33.500
There is a special
word pattern just

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:35.560
for colors, which is weird.

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:36.660
I kind of like it.

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:38.520
The tenses were
identical to Esperanto's.

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:40.478
It had this correlative
system that was, again,

00:10:40.478 --> 00:10:42.040
identical to Esperanto's.

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:43.840
All of it was purely lifted.

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:47.160
And in the beginning,
when I'd just started out,

00:10:47.160 --> 00:10:52.060
I actually started to translate
Shakespeare's "The Tempest"

00:10:52.060 --> 00:10:53.730
into this language.

00:10:53.730 --> 00:10:58.370
And it just keeps going like
that, which sounds impressive

00:10:58.370 --> 00:11:02.030
until you know how palely
derivative the language is.

00:11:02.030 --> 00:11:04.290
In fact, I get
this question a lot

00:11:04.290 --> 00:11:06.880
about, oh, wow, how do you
create a full language that's

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:07.740
functional?

00:11:07.740 --> 00:11:09.490
That's actually not hard.

00:11:09.490 --> 00:11:12.340
It's not hard to create a
language that is completely

00:11:12.340 --> 00:11:15.620
and fully functional, can
do everything you want.

00:11:15.620 --> 00:11:18.790
It's fairly easy if
you're going to copy

00:11:18.790 --> 00:11:20.990
a lot of things wholesale
from other languages

00:11:20.990 --> 00:11:22.810
and just basically recode them.

00:11:22.810 --> 00:11:25.600
Then all it takes is the simple
matter of just coding it over.

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:27.314
It's like if you're
talking about drawing

00:11:27.314 --> 00:11:29.730
a human, it's like, wow, it
must be tough to draw a human.

00:11:29.730 --> 00:11:30.840
It's not hard.

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:33.150
There you go.

00:11:33.150 --> 00:11:33.880
It's a human.

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:37.379
We all recognize it's
basically a human.

00:11:37.379 --> 00:11:37.920
I don't know.

00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:40.840
He's rubbing his belly while
he's pointing, I guess.

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:43.959
But of course, what
you mean when you say,

00:11:43.959 --> 00:11:45.375
oh, it's hard to
draw a human, you

00:11:45.375 --> 00:11:48.314
mean it's hard to draw a
human that looks realistic.

00:11:48.314 --> 00:11:49.730
It's easy enough
to draw something

00:11:49.730 --> 00:11:51.140
that's basically a human.

00:11:51.140 --> 00:11:54.490
Kids get it by the time
they're three or four.

00:11:54.490 --> 00:11:55.870
Same is true of a language.

00:11:55.870 --> 00:11:57.820
Easy to create a fully
functional language.

00:11:57.820 --> 00:11:59.680
Difficult to create
a language that

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:01.530
actually looks like
a real language

00:12:01.530 --> 00:12:03.620
that we speak here on Earth.

00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:06.210
And so for me, the
real watershed moment

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:08.790
was when I found other
language creators online,

00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:11.020
the early conlang community,
the conlang listserv.

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:11.978
This is an early photo.

00:12:11.978 --> 00:12:13.600
And I'm sorry this
can't blow up more.

00:12:13.600 --> 00:12:15.060
It was taken with an old camera.

00:12:15.060 --> 00:12:17.790
From the first Language
Creation Conference in 2006,

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:21.190
where a lot of language creators
met for the very first time

00:12:21.190 --> 00:12:21.800
in person.

00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:23.840
Before that, it was
all online interaction.

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:28.560
But basically, I found
this listserv in late 2000.

00:12:28.560 --> 00:12:29.206
I joined up.

00:12:29.206 --> 00:12:31.580
I started reading some messages,
people talking about all

00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:32.410
these different languages.

00:12:32.410 --> 00:12:35.010
And I was like, what do you
mean Tolkien created languages?

00:12:35.010 --> 00:12:35.759
The "Hobbit" guy?

00:12:35.759 --> 00:12:36.550
I didn't know that.

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:38.216
Didn't know that
Klingon was a language.

00:12:38.216 --> 00:12:39.700
I didn't know any of that.

00:12:39.700 --> 00:12:41.940
And so at first,
of course, which

00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:43.970
is what naturally
happens when you

00:12:43.970 --> 00:12:45.940
think you've been doing
something really great

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:47.650
and you see something
vastly different,

00:12:47.650 --> 00:12:50.030
you think, well, they're just
doing it wrong, of course.

00:12:50.030 --> 00:12:52.120
I'm the one who's
really the cool person.

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:53.620
And I thought that
at the beginning.

00:12:53.620 --> 00:12:57.360
But as I started to really
look at other people's work,

00:12:57.360 --> 00:12:59.920
and study their work, and
follow all these conversations,

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:03.580
and see what was going
on, that was when I said,

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:07.070
oh, I think I understand
what I've done here.

00:13:07.070 --> 00:13:10.414
And this literally
225-page dictionary

00:13:10.414 --> 00:13:12.830
and reference grammar that
I've created for this language,

00:13:12.830 --> 00:13:15.580
Megdevi, is total garbage.

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:17.785
And so it was then
on that it was

00:13:17.785 --> 00:13:19.450
like that was my moment zero.

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:22.480
I started over, and
I started learning.

00:13:22.480 --> 00:13:26.280
And that's basically what
I started in late 2000,

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:29.940
and what I've continued
to do even now.

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:34.140
And I think one of the
most important things that

00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:36.430
happened to me when I
keyed in with the community

00:13:36.430 --> 00:13:39.270
is I started to ask myself
questions that I had never

00:13:39.270 --> 00:13:42.900
considered before, questions
that I'd never imagined before.

00:13:42.900 --> 00:13:44.360
So I'll give you an example.

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:46.830
We have this word
"corner" here in English.

00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:49.600
And so presuming--
there's no tricks here--

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:53.480
that this box is just an empty
box, how many corners have we

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:54.432
got here?

00:13:54.432 --> 00:13:55.099
AUDIENCE: Eight.

00:13:55.099 --> 00:13:56.265
DAVID PETERSON: There we go.

00:13:56.265 --> 00:13:56.850
Eight.

00:13:56.850 --> 00:13:58.475
I know somebody said
four, but yeah, we

00:13:58.475 --> 00:14:00.350
have eight corners right there.

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:04.960
It's slightly different if you
ask this question in Spanish.

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:06.387
"Cuantos esquinas hay?"

00:14:06.387 --> 00:14:07.970
Anybody who speaks
Spanish is probably

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:09.678
going to know what
the answer to this is.

00:14:09.678 --> 00:14:11.980
"Esquinas" is essentially
a word for "corner."

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:14.030
And the answer to
this question is four.

00:14:14.030 --> 00:14:16.140
There are only
four esquinas alla.

00:14:16.140 --> 00:14:18.970
And they are those
on the outside.

00:14:18.970 --> 00:14:22.970
If you ask a different question,
"Cuantos rincones hay?"

00:14:22.970 --> 00:14:24.860
Then you get a different answer.

00:14:24.860 --> 00:14:27.520
There are four, and they're
the interior corners.

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:29.870
Because, in fact, there
are two different words

00:14:29.870 --> 00:14:32.460
for that concept in Spanish.

00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:36.110
And if you think about it,
it's actually quite important.

00:14:36.110 --> 00:14:38.000
When somebody says
something like,

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.790
oh, watch out for that
table, don't hit your hip

00:14:40.790 --> 00:14:44.670
on the corner, you know
exactly what corner they mean.

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:47.540
It's hard, and
frankly, it would be

00:14:47.540 --> 00:14:52.580
really impressive to hit your
hip on the corner of a room.

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:54.537
Like you'd have to
get it right in there.

00:14:54.537 --> 00:14:55.620
It'd be really impressive.

00:14:55.620 --> 00:14:59.130
It's like watching the little
DVD bouncing logo, right?

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:00.380
And you just keep watching it.

00:15:00.380 --> 00:15:02.171
It's like, god, it's
gonna hit that corner,

00:15:02.171 --> 00:15:03.550
it's gonna hit that corner.

00:15:03.550 --> 00:15:05.555
Oh, it just barely missed it.

00:15:05.555 --> 00:15:07.180
It's like, yeah,
that's an achievement.

00:15:07.180 --> 00:15:10.040
So anyway, that's just
something that, if you

00:15:10.040 --> 00:15:13.340
don't know Spanish, you never
would have thought of before

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:15.050
if your language was English.

00:15:15.050 --> 00:15:15.920
Corners are corners.

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:18.880
Well, it turns out they don't
necessarily need to be so.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:21.390
Another one, and this
is just phonologically,

00:15:21.390 --> 00:15:23.760
we have these two words,
"spit" and "pit" in English.

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:25.340
They're actually different.

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:28.080
And you can tell if you
put your hand right up

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:29.420
in front of your face.

00:15:29.420 --> 00:15:35.550
And focus on the P, and say
"spit," and now say "pit."

00:15:35.550 --> 00:15:37.370
And if you'll notice
for the second one,

00:15:37.370 --> 00:15:40.080
there is quite more
of a burst of air

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:43.380
because, in fact, the
second one is aspirated.

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:46.110
In English though, we don't
think of these Ps as different.

00:15:46.110 --> 00:15:47.690
Like the P in
"spit" is basically

00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:50.119
the same as the P in
"pit" and whatever.

00:15:50.119 --> 00:15:51.910
Sound engineers know
they're different when

00:15:51.910 --> 00:15:54.030
you have a handheld mic
in front of your face

00:15:54.030 --> 00:15:55.650
because it's really annoying.

00:15:55.650 --> 00:15:59.250
But otherwise, we think of
them as basically the same.

00:15:59.250 --> 00:16:02.030
Whereas in other languages,
they can be quite different.

00:16:02.030 --> 00:16:06.766
So these are two words of
Hindi-- "tal" and then "thal."

00:16:06.766 --> 00:16:08.390
And they're completely
different words.

00:16:08.390 --> 00:16:10.640
And you can see that they're
even spelled differently,

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:12.240
"tal" and "thal."

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:14.345
The first one means "postpone."

00:16:14.345 --> 00:16:15.720
And then the second
one, I guess,

00:16:15.720 --> 00:16:18.790
refers to some sort of a
place where you can buy wood.

00:16:18.790 --> 00:16:21.731
I've gotten "wood shop," "lumber
yard," "lumber shop," something

00:16:21.731 --> 00:16:22.230
like that.

00:16:22.230 --> 00:16:24.220
I hope it's actually
still a word of Hindi.

00:16:24.220 --> 00:16:26.466
If there isn't, somebody
can leave a nasty note

00:16:26.466 --> 00:16:28.590
in the comments-- that's
not a word we use anymore.

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:30.131
It means something
totally different.

00:16:30.131 --> 00:16:32.110
But anyway, it
illustrates the basic idea

00:16:32.110 --> 00:16:36.970
that this aspiration, which is
just a background note of how

00:16:36.970 --> 00:16:41.310
you properly speak
English, is functional

00:16:41.310 --> 00:16:43.390
in a different language
like Hindi and very,

00:16:43.390 --> 00:16:47.030
very important in order to
make yourself understood.

00:16:47.030 --> 00:16:49.199
In fact, even this
past Monday, I'm

00:16:49.199 --> 00:16:50.490
constantly learning new things.

00:16:50.490 --> 00:16:52.640
This was an example
that somebody

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:54.390
from the conlang
community, William Annis,

00:16:54.390 --> 00:16:55.870
found and showed me.

00:16:55.870 --> 00:16:57.830
This is Amharic.

00:16:57.830 --> 00:17:00.940
And it's an absolutely
fascinating little facet

00:17:00.940 --> 00:17:03.744
that I never would have
even imagined as possible.

00:17:03.744 --> 00:17:06.160
These are two sentences. "The
judge judged against Aster,"

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:08.430
and then "The judge
judged in Aster's favor."

00:17:08.430 --> 00:17:10.180
They're basically opposites.

00:17:10.180 --> 00:17:13.359
And what's happening is the verb
is at the end of the sentence.

00:17:13.359 --> 00:17:16.380
And I want you to look
at these parts of it.

00:17:16.380 --> 00:17:18.920
Essentially, the
verb is agreeing

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:22.240
with the little preposition that
means against somebody's favor

00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:27.130
or in favor of somebody,
which is just wild.

00:17:27.130 --> 00:17:29.550
I've heard of applicatives,
but usually, that

00:17:29.550 --> 00:17:32.009
involves some sort of
switch up of the arguments

00:17:32.009 --> 00:17:33.800
and changing the
structures and everything.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:36.570
This looks just like agreement
with a really weird thing

00:17:36.570 --> 00:17:37.330
to agree with.

00:17:37.330 --> 00:17:38.990
And that's just awesome.

00:17:38.990 --> 00:17:39.640
Oh!

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:42.340
It just gets me
up in the morning.

00:17:42.340 --> 00:17:46.370
Anyway, so being a part
of the conlang community,

00:17:46.370 --> 00:17:47.430
this is what I gained.

00:17:47.430 --> 00:17:50.740
You gain, essentially, an
understanding of the ways

00:17:50.740 --> 00:17:52.880
that languages
can and do differ.

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:56.470
And then once you have
that, you get to a point

00:17:56.470 --> 00:17:58.850
where you realize,
basically, all right,

00:17:58.850 --> 00:18:01.180
languages can do
pretty much anything.

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:03.340
So then when you sit down
to create a language,

00:18:03.340 --> 00:18:05.650
you really are
saying, what is it

00:18:05.650 --> 00:18:08.010
that I want to do
with this language?

00:18:08.010 --> 00:18:10.300
I have all of the
options before me.

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:12.550
And now what am I
going to do with it?

00:18:12.550 --> 00:18:15.020
And so for example, if
you ask me right now,

00:18:15.020 --> 00:18:18.100
just a quick example,
what the word for "corner"

00:18:18.100 --> 00:18:21.770
is in Dothraki, it's "kemikhof."

00:18:21.770 --> 00:18:23.740
And there actually
isn't a distinction

00:18:23.740 --> 00:18:27.400
between an interior and exterior
corner, but not by accident.

00:18:27.400 --> 00:18:29.390
It's because I wanted
it to be that way.

00:18:29.390 --> 00:18:32.020
And in fact, it has to do
with the unique etymology

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:32.950
of the word.

00:18:32.950 --> 00:18:36.750
It ultimately comes from a word
"kem," which means "conjoined."

00:18:36.750 --> 00:18:41.110
And so how the
word came to be is

00:18:41.110 --> 00:18:44.070
that it's talking about
the meeting of two walls

00:18:44.070 --> 00:18:46.320
or the meeting of two things.

00:18:46.320 --> 00:18:47.840
And so that's what
it's focusing on,

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:50.440
not the interactional
properties of the human,

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:52.750
but actually what it
is and what it's doing.

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:54.770
And so that's why
there's only one

00:18:54.770 --> 00:18:56.760
word for "corner" in Dothraki.

00:18:56.760 --> 00:19:00.460
It was something I did on
purpose, not by accident.

00:19:00.460 --> 00:19:05.320
So now that I'm here,
I wanted to give you

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:09.820
an in-depth example of
the type of questioning

00:19:09.820 --> 00:19:12.152
I do when it comes to
translation and things

00:19:12.152 --> 00:19:12.860
that I work with.

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:17.250
So this is a script page from
the first season of "Defiance,"

00:19:17.250 --> 00:19:20.740
where this entire exchange
is in the Irathient language.

00:19:20.740 --> 00:19:23.170
And we're going to focus on
this first sentence, which

00:19:23.170 --> 00:19:28.320
is an elder Irathient is saying,
"It's how the Castis killed us

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:29.720
in the Great Diaspora.

00:19:29.720 --> 00:19:32.610
Caves filled with chlorine gas."

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:34.950
So I got that, and I
think, well, of course,

00:19:34.950 --> 00:19:37.382
I don't have a word
for "chlorine gas."

00:19:37.382 --> 00:19:38.840
So what am I going
to do with that?

00:19:38.840 --> 00:19:40.300
How am I going to
translate that?

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:43.235
To catch you up to speed, for
those who are not familiar

00:19:43.235 --> 00:19:45.360
with "Defiance," I'm going
to need to introduce you

00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:46.080
to some aliens.

00:19:46.080 --> 00:19:47.860
First, there are the Irathients.

00:19:47.860 --> 00:19:48.770
They look like this.

00:19:48.770 --> 00:19:52.450
They have orange hair like that.

00:19:52.450 --> 00:19:56.480
Their planet was previously,
before the show started,

00:19:56.480 --> 00:20:00.070
conquered by the Castithans.

00:20:00.070 --> 00:20:03.820
And basically, at some
time in the distant past,

00:20:03.820 --> 00:20:05.820
it was like the Norman conquest.

00:20:05.820 --> 00:20:06.566
They came.

00:20:06.566 --> 00:20:07.190
They took over.

00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:09.140
They became the
rulers for a while.

00:20:09.140 --> 00:20:10.890
Now, they're on more
or less even footing,

00:20:10.890 --> 00:20:13.600
but there's still some
tensions due to the history.

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:16.480
And then a third set of
aliens are the Indogenes.

00:20:16.480 --> 00:20:19.340
The Indogenes are responsible
for pretty much all

00:20:19.340 --> 00:20:22.090
of the technology that
the rest of the aliens--

00:20:22.090 --> 00:20:24.640
called, collectively,
the Votans-- enjoy.

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:26.910
So they created all
of the spaceships,

00:20:26.910 --> 00:20:29.110
all of the nanotechnology,
everything.

00:20:29.110 --> 00:20:33.460
And they are, themselves,
an interesting creation.

00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:35.650
They modify themselves
genetically.

00:20:35.650 --> 00:20:37.310
They have implants
all over the place.

00:20:37.310 --> 00:20:39.660
Their eyes can act
like microscopes.

00:20:39.660 --> 00:20:43.220
Their hands can do really
fantastic little machinations.

00:20:43.220 --> 00:20:46.260
So for example,
with their language,

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:49.360
their writing system is
actually a post-hoc creation.

00:20:49.360 --> 00:20:51.910
Every single glyph
in the language,

00:20:51.910 --> 00:20:55.870
whether it's for a number
or a syllable or whatever,

00:20:55.870 --> 00:20:59.420
has these little
conjoined double hexagons.

00:20:59.420 --> 00:21:03.140
This is nothing that would
ever arise in a natural context

00:21:03.140 --> 00:21:06.220
because it's way too complex
to draw with your hand

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:07.350
and get it right.

00:21:07.350 --> 00:21:11.880
But Indogenes can do it exactly
right every single time because

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:13.450
of their augmentations.

00:21:13.450 --> 00:21:15.450
And so they actually
created this writing system

00:21:15.450 --> 00:21:17.752
for themselves after
the point in time

00:21:17.752 --> 00:21:19.460
where they started
augmenting themselves.

00:21:19.460 --> 00:21:21.870
Anyway, so this is
their number system.

00:21:21.870 --> 00:21:24.140
Their number system is base 7.

00:21:24.140 --> 00:21:28.010
And you'll see why it's base
7 if you see how the number

00:21:28.010 --> 00:21:28.900
system works there.

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:31.290
So you can see the
little tick mark

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:34.570
going do do do as
we go from azu,

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:37.170
kizu, fozu, dezu, nuzu, hazu.

00:21:37.170 --> 00:21:39.970
And then that's
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.

00:21:39.970 --> 00:21:44.410
And then ama, you switch
the suffix, and you get 7.

00:21:44.410 --> 00:21:50.000
So basically, their 7 is the
equivalent to our 10, like 1-0.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:52.860
So I started with
them when I need

00:21:52.860 --> 00:21:55.760
to come up with words
for the elements--

00:21:55.760 --> 00:21:57.800
the periodic table of elements.

00:21:57.800 --> 00:22:00.730
I reasoned that they would
be the ones to kind of codify

00:22:00.730 --> 00:22:03.080
and then really
make use of this,

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:05.030
and they actually
invented a system

00:22:05.030 --> 00:22:09.850
for referring to the
periodic elements.

00:22:09.850 --> 00:22:11.400
They did it by protons.

00:22:11.400 --> 00:22:15.250
So chlorine has 17 protons.

00:22:15.250 --> 00:22:18.650
17 in base 7 is 23.

00:22:18.650 --> 00:22:21.770
What that means is that the
digit 2 followed by the digit 3

00:22:21.770 --> 00:22:24.470
equals 17 in base 7.

00:22:24.470 --> 00:22:28.970
Then the word for
17, 23 in base 7.

00:22:28.970 --> 00:22:31.580
You have kima which
is basically 20.

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:33.970
Remember, that's the number
2 with the ma suffix,

00:22:33.970 --> 00:22:35.760
and now you see the
2 lines and then also

00:22:35.760 --> 00:22:38.270
the straight line up
and down in the middle.

00:22:38.270 --> 00:22:40.660
That's 20, and then 3
of course we know, fozu.

00:22:40.660 --> 00:22:44.300
So 23, or 17, is kimafozu.

00:22:44.300 --> 00:22:47.940
They also have a suffix, vun.

00:22:47.940 --> 00:22:49.030
This was an older suffix.

00:22:49.030 --> 00:22:51.363
Basically the word vun used
to mean just something like,

00:22:51.363 --> 00:22:52.710
stuff way back when.

00:22:52.710 --> 00:22:54.870
Now it's a suffix
you can add to things

00:22:54.870 --> 00:22:56.900
to make a kind of
nominal compound,

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:59.090
and specifically they
add it to numbers

00:22:59.090 --> 00:23:02.990
to create a word that
means "that element."

00:23:02.990 --> 00:23:08.400
So when you add vun to
17 you get chlorine.

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:09.710
Kimafozuvun.

00:23:09.710 --> 00:23:10.477
Kimafozuvun.

00:23:10.477 --> 00:23:11.810
Yeah, sorry, I can say it right.

00:23:11.810 --> 00:23:13.190
And of course you can
spell it like that

00:23:13.190 --> 00:23:14.260
with the numbers
in front, or you

00:23:14.260 --> 00:23:15.310
can spell it all the way out.

00:23:15.310 --> 00:23:17.431
It's basically the equivalent
of this in English.

00:23:17.431 --> 00:23:18.930
You know spelling
twelfth like that.

00:23:18.930 --> 00:23:20.255
God I love it.

00:23:20.255 --> 00:23:20.880
Oh, it stopped.

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:22.480
All right.

00:23:22.480 --> 00:23:24.160
Anyway, so twelfth,
12, all right.

00:23:24.160 --> 00:23:27.150
So we've created this
word now in Indogene,

00:23:27.150 --> 00:23:30.120
or the Indogene language
which is called Indojisnen.

00:23:30.120 --> 00:23:33.600
Next step is to borrow
that into Castithan.

00:23:33.600 --> 00:23:36.010
And the reason is that
Castithan is essentially

00:23:36.010 --> 00:23:39.210
the language of commerce,
politics, everything.

00:23:39.210 --> 00:23:42.870
It's the English
of the Votan world.

00:23:42.870 --> 00:23:45.440
So they borrowed all of
their scientific terminology

00:23:45.440 --> 00:23:47.840
from Indogene, or Indojisnen.

00:23:47.840 --> 00:23:50.490
So that gets borrowed in, and
it gets borrowed in pretty well.

00:23:50.490 --> 00:23:54.250
So it's kimafozuvun
in Indojisnen and then

00:23:54.250 --> 00:23:58.300
in Castithan it's kimafozuvuno.

00:23:58.300 --> 00:24:02.690
You have to add the O suffix
on there to make it functional.

00:24:02.690 --> 00:24:04.990
Then you have this
word in Castithan.

00:24:04.990 --> 00:24:07.450
By the way there are some
quirks-- little aside

00:24:07.450 --> 00:24:10.330
with this spelling because
Castithan spelling is kind of

00:24:10.330 --> 00:24:11.940
slightly more
difficult than English,

00:24:11.940 --> 00:24:13.770
but slightly less
difficult than Tibetan.

00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:16.080
Tibetan I think is
the most difficult

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:17.730
that we've created
on the planet.

00:24:17.730 --> 00:24:18.600
So just some notes.

00:24:18.600 --> 00:24:21.530
Like for example, you could
write ki this way, or this way.

00:24:21.530 --> 00:24:23.446
The reason is that there
are 2 different types

00:24:23.446 --> 00:24:25.320
of K's in the history.

00:24:25.320 --> 00:24:28.520
-So you have this older word,
which had a long vowel "li-ku,"

00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:31.470
which is now pronounced ligo,
and it refers to some sort

00:24:31.470 --> 00:24:32.290
of small animal.

00:24:32.290 --> 00:24:34.529
That's using, essentially,
the traditional K.

00:24:34.529 --> 00:24:36.820
And you'll see that the
traditional K is now pronounced

00:24:36.820 --> 00:24:39.030
G in certain circumstances.

00:24:39.030 --> 00:24:44.220
However, the old ejective K
which is here for the word

00:24:44.220 --> 00:24:47.400
"ni-k'u" which is now
pronounced "nico," and it means,

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:48.900
kind of, lot or parcel.

00:24:48.900 --> 00:24:51.520
That one is always
pronounced K no matter

00:24:51.520 --> 00:24:52.650
where it is in the word.

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:56.230
So when they do borrowings they
tend to use that special K,

00:24:56.230 --> 00:25:00.380
just to make sure that everybody
knows it's always pronounced K.

00:25:00.380 --> 00:25:01.670
Same thing kind of here.

00:25:01.670 --> 00:25:03.120
These are both
pronounced the same

00:25:03.120 --> 00:25:05.030
but the one with the
longer vowel-- or that

00:25:05.030 --> 00:25:07.490
used to be the longer vowel--
is always going to be pronounced

00:25:07.490 --> 00:25:07.990
ma.

00:25:07.990 --> 00:25:10.130
So we use that, just to be safe.

00:25:10.130 --> 00:25:12.850
And same, the first
Z also changes

00:25:12.850 --> 00:25:14.150
in certain circumstances.

00:25:14.150 --> 00:25:15.230
The second Z does not.

00:25:15.230 --> 00:25:18.410
So you use the second Z
when spelling things out.

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:21.090
That gets us kima and zu.

00:25:21.090 --> 00:25:23.640
This one has a slightly
different explanation.

00:25:23.640 --> 00:25:25.710
So these are the
non-sibilant fricatives

00:25:25.710 --> 00:25:28.120
that have a different story.

00:25:28.120 --> 00:25:30.430
F is pronounced F at the
beginning of the word.

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:33.980
It tends to be pronounced to
V in the middle of the word.

00:25:33.980 --> 00:25:35.669
So for example we
have this word that

00:25:35.669 --> 00:25:36.960
used to be pronounced that way.

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:38.330
It's pronounced fozwo, ritual.

00:25:38.330 --> 00:25:40.121
It's a nice F at the
beginning of the word.

00:25:40.121 --> 00:25:42.359
In between you had this
older word, hiifau,

00:25:42.359 --> 00:25:43.400
which is pronounced hivo.

00:25:43.400 --> 00:25:44.380
It's that word for shirt.

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:46.505
It's pronounced like a V
in the middle of the word.

00:25:46.505 --> 00:25:49.404
But since there are
no other fantastic

00:25:49.404 --> 00:25:51.320
ways of representing the
A, it's kind of known

00:25:51.320 --> 00:25:55.855
that you have to swap out
for the sibilant fricative

00:25:55.855 --> 00:25:57.480
since there's two
versions of each one.

00:25:57.480 --> 00:25:58.670
There's 2 Z's and 2 S's.

00:25:58.670 --> 00:26:00.320
There aren't 2 F's.

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:03.280
So you just use the regular
F in a borrowed word

00:26:03.280 --> 00:26:05.320
and you know that rather
than being pronounced V

00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:07.780
it's pronounced F
because it's a borrowing.

00:26:07.780 --> 00:26:11.200
The same is true of the original
V, which is often pronounced H

00:26:11.200 --> 00:26:12.310
in between vowels.

00:26:12.310 --> 00:26:14.476
You know it's pronounced V
because it's a borrowing.

00:26:14.476 --> 00:26:17.440
So that's how you get the
spelling of kimafozuvuno

00:26:17.440 --> 00:26:19.360
in Castithan.

00:26:19.360 --> 00:26:21.290
The reason we had
create it in Castithan

00:26:21.290 --> 00:26:24.040
is because a lot of the
borrowings in a Irathient

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:26.650
that have to do with
technology come from Castithan.

00:26:26.650 --> 00:26:28.900
Usually via Indojisnen,
but Castithan

00:26:28.900 --> 00:26:32.000
is where they got a lot of
terminology because of the time

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:35.570
when Castithans were essentially
in charge of everything.

00:26:35.570 --> 00:26:38.800
So that gets borrowed
into Irathient this way,

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:40.610
and it's now kimafozvun.

00:26:40.610 --> 00:26:42.610
Notice that we lost a U there.

00:26:42.610 --> 00:26:46.070
That's because they're used
to having to remove vowels

00:26:46.070 --> 00:26:50.560
in between sibilants and
secondary consonants,

00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:56.070
moving from Castithan to
Irathient because that just

00:26:56.070 --> 00:26:57.610
happens a lot with
Castithan words.

00:26:57.610 --> 00:26:59.750
So they saw this one and
said, well there probably

00:26:59.750 --> 00:27:01.489
isn't a real U there.

00:27:01.489 --> 00:27:03.030
Even though there
was a real U there,

00:27:03.030 --> 00:27:04.738
they thought there
wasn't a real U there.

00:27:04.738 --> 00:27:07.810
It's the same kind of thing
that happened with-- what's

00:27:07.810 --> 00:27:10.210
a good example from English?

00:27:10.210 --> 00:27:11.570
Like, nuncle.

00:27:11.570 --> 00:27:13.100
I think it was
originally nuncle,

00:27:13.100 --> 00:27:15.150
but now we call it
uncle because we

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:18.820
thought people were saying
"an uncle" as opposed to,

00:27:18.820 --> 00:27:20.709
"a nuncle".

00:27:20.709 --> 00:27:21.250
Really weird.

00:27:21.250 --> 00:27:23.115
Anyway, so at it's
that type of a thing.

00:27:23.115 --> 00:27:24.490
Now as for the
word itself-- this

00:27:24.490 --> 00:27:26.710
is just another
kind of a fun aside.

00:27:26.710 --> 00:27:28.910
Irathient has a
series of noun classes

00:27:28.910 --> 00:27:31.830
that are indicated by
the initial consonant.

00:27:31.830 --> 00:27:36.150
And it just so happens that
since this word begins with a K

00:27:36.150 --> 00:27:40.190
it falls into the
dangerous animal class.

00:27:40.190 --> 00:27:42.870
So klaidi is a dangerous insect.

00:27:42.870 --> 00:27:45.940
Kombisi is a kind of a
tentacle beast comes from above

00:27:45.940 --> 00:27:47.490
and sucks you up.

00:27:47.490 --> 00:27:56.170
Then kangezi Is a word for like
the alpha of a pack of animals.

00:27:56.170 --> 00:28:00.650
So for that reason they treated
this like this was the root.

00:28:00.650 --> 00:28:04.360
That the root was actually
imafozvun and that

00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:07.330
the K was incidental, and
indicative of a class 4

00:28:07.330 --> 00:28:08.130
membership.

00:28:08.130 --> 00:28:10.900
Which means that they created
this word, rimafozvun,

00:28:10.900 --> 00:28:14.000
which means chlorine the
element, or the substance.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:18.360
Then kimafozvun, which is
now the dangerous animal

00:28:18.360 --> 00:28:20.130
and has the concept
of danger in it,

00:28:20.130 --> 00:28:23.860
is used specifically
for chlorine gas, which

00:28:23.860 --> 00:28:28.100
is what the Castithan's used to
kill them back in the old days.

00:28:28.100 --> 00:28:32.700
And that is basically the story
for translating just that word,

00:28:32.700 --> 00:28:35.542
in that sentence, in that
scene, in that episode,

00:28:35.542 --> 00:28:36.500
in the show "Defiance."

00:28:36.500 --> 00:28:42.510
So that's kind of the process I
go through when I create words,

00:28:42.510 --> 00:28:45.790
and basically it's all
thanks to the education

00:28:45.790 --> 00:28:48.910
that I had coming up through
the conlang community.

00:28:48.910 --> 00:28:51.770
I know to ask questions that
I never knew to ask before.

00:28:51.770 --> 00:28:55.760
And so one of the
things that I realized

00:28:55.760 --> 00:28:58.360
when we had this great
shift in the internet

00:28:58.360 --> 00:28:59.610
and how we interacted with it.

00:28:59.610 --> 00:29:02.660
I don't know if it
was 2009, 2010, 2011,

00:29:02.660 --> 00:29:06.940
but it was that time
where suddenly nobody

00:29:06.940 --> 00:29:09.190
was using hand-coded
HTML anymore

00:29:09.190 --> 00:29:11.450
for their own personal websites.

00:29:11.450 --> 00:29:17.280
People kind of were going away
from listservs and bulletin

00:29:17.280 --> 00:29:20.030
boards even, and
instead were interacting

00:29:20.030 --> 00:29:23.400
through micro-blogging
platforms,

00:29:23.400 --> 00:29:26.320
blogging platforms,
social media platforms.

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:29.020
I started to see a lot of
conlangers coming to the art,

00:29:29.020 --> 00:29:32.810
especially with a lot of popular
media like "Avatar," and "Game

00:29:32.810 --> 00:29:37.140
of Thrones," who knew those
shows but didn't know anything

00:29:37.140 --> 00:29:39.130
about the old
conlanging community,

00:29:39.130 --> 00:29:41.010
and who definitely
at this point in time

00:29:41.010 --> 00:29:43.120
were not going to
join an email based

00:29:43.120 --> 00:29:45.920
listserv where they communicate
with people via email.

00:29:45.920 --> 00:29:49.570
Like, it's not even a part
of our vocabulary anymore.

00:29:49.570 --> 00:29:53.435
And so, the thing was though,
I felt like the education

00:29:53.435 --> 00:29:58.210
that I had, which I thought
was fantastic, was being lost,

00:29:58.210 --> 00:29:59.600
and is essentially
irrecoverable.

00:29:59.600 --> 00:30:01.930
Even though like you can
search all of the archives

00:30:01.930 --> 00:30:04.138
on the conlang listserv--
they're publicly available,

00:30:04.138 --> 00:30:06.677
there's great stuff there,
nobody's going to look at it,

00:30:06.677 --> 00:30:08.260
nobody's going to
pull it up, nobody's

00:30:08.260 --> 00:30:09.700
going to go through
and read old emails.

00:30:09.700 --> 00:30:10.890
It's not going to happen.

00:30:10.890 --> 00:30:12.300
And so that was
one of the things

00:30:12.300 --> 00:30:14.431
I hope to do with this
book, "The Art of Language

00:30:14.431 --> 00:30:14.930
Invention."

00:30:14.930 --> 00:30:17.820
I'm kind of trying to rescue
some of that knowledge

00:30:17.820 --> 00:30:19.440
and put it somewhere.

00:30:19.440 --> 00:30:22.410
Oddly enough into old
media, hardcover, book form

00:30:22.410 --> 00:30:26.204
because I think people that are
conlangers that are primarily

00:30:26.204 --> 00:30:27.620
on Twitter and
Tumblr are actually

00:30:27.620 --> 00:30:29.203
more likely to get
this book than they

00:30:29.203 --> 00:30:31.680
are to actually pull up the
old archives of an email list,

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:32.990
or join it.

00:30:32.990 --> 00:30:36.302
Which is a really weird
thing-- weird reality

00:30:36.302 --> 00:30:38.010
we live in but it's
kind of where we are.

00:30:38.010 --> 00:30:43.030
So that was kind of my
fondest hope and purpose

00:30:43.030 --> 00:30:45.940
for this book is to kind
of capture that put it

00:30:45.940 --> 00:30:48.660
somewhere so that other
people could benefit by it.

00:30:48.660 --> 00:30:50.610
And so it's not
even like my stuff.

00:30:50.610 --> 00:30:53.140
It's the stuff that I
learned and basically

00:30:53.140 --> 00:30:56.420
just put into this capsule.

00:30:56.420 --> 00:31:00.050
So anyway, that's the
story behind this book.

00:31:00.050 --> 00:31:02.510
Thank you guys so much for
your time and listening,

00:31:02.510 --> 00:31:06.200
and if you get it,
I hope you enjoy it.

