00:33:43.260 --> 00:33:51.960
and when I was taking Arabic,
and Esperanto, and Russian,

00:33:51.960 --> 00:33:53.550
and Linguistics 5.

00:33:53.550 --> 00:33:56.750
It turns out I wasn't taking
those classes at that time.

00:33:56.750 --> 00:33:59.230
I did take Arabic
and Esperanto, but I

00:33:59.230 --> 00:34:01.880
took Russian and linguistics
the next semester

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:04.160
in the fall of 2000.

00:34:04.160 --> 00:34:06.446
So I took Russian
and linguistics.

00:34:06.446 --> 00:34:08.070
I had previously
taken a year of Arabic

00:34:08.070 --> 00:34:09.800
and a semester of
Esperanto, and I

00:34:09.800 --> 00:34:13.570
started creating my first
language at the exact same time

00:34:13.570 --> 00:34:16.070
that I was taking my very first
introduction to linguistics,

00:34:16.070 --> 00:34:17.445
which I had never
heard of before

00:34:17.445 --> 00:34:20.110
and I only took because it
was a breadth requirement.

00:34:20.110 --> 00:34:22.888
But I think it was
like 2 or 3 weeks

00:34:22.888 --> 00:34:25.179
in-- I actually have the date
if I go back to my notes,

00:34:25.179 --> 00:34:25.590
but I forget.

00:34:25.590 --> 00:34:26.210
Anyway.

00:34:26.210 --> 00:34:29.690
So I kind of started growing
as a language creator

00:34:29.690 --> 00:34:31.550
as I was learning linguistics.

00:34:31.550 --> 00:34:34.290
Oh, but I eventually did finish
out with a linguistics major,

00:34:34.290 --> 00:34:36.650
and I also got my master's
degree in linguistics

00:34:36.650 --> 00:34:38.960
at UC San Diego.

00:34:38.960 --> 00:34:43.060
Definitely the study did
inform a lot of what I did

00:34:43.060 --> 00:34:45.989
but at the same time
it was helpful to have

00:34:45.989 --> 00:34:48.394
the background of
a language creator

00:34:48.394 --> 00:34:52.360
so that I could know to, kind
of interpret what I was learning

00:34:52.360 --> 00:34:56.230
in linguistics with more of an
artistic and also critical eye.

00:34:56.230 --> 00:34:58.940
Especially a lot of
the theoretical stuff.

00:34:58.940 --> 00:35:03.630
Like theoretical
syntax has not really

00:35:03.630 --> 00:35:07.230
informed what I'm
doing at all, but a lot

00:35:07.230 --> 00:35:09.520
of what I studied in
morphology, especially

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:11.585
like lexical morphology,
[? word and ?] paradigm

00:35:11.585 --> 00:35:13.210
morphology, and a
lot of what I studied

00:35:13.210 --> 00:35:16.910
in historical linguistics has
informed what I do enormously,

00:35:16.910 --> 00:35:20.770
enormously, and definitely
phonology to, and typology,

00:35:20.770 --> 00:35:22.134
typology is huge.

00:35:22.134 --> 00:35:23.550
There was a lot
of back and forth.

00:35:23.550 --> 00:35:27.930
But anyway, a lot of it came
in and definitely linguistics

00:35:27.930 --> 00:35:30.750
was an important part of my
education as a conlanger.

00:35:30.750 --> 00:35:32.930
But I would say equally
important, if not

00:35:32.930 --> 00:35:38.140
more important, was my education
from other language creators.

00:35:38.140 --> 00:35:40.630
AUDIENCE: I was interested
in birth of language.

00:35:40.630 --> 00:35:42.870
Have you investigated that?

00:35:42.870 --> 00:35:45.500
DAVID PETERSON: What,
like language at all?

00:35:45.500 --> 00:35:48.890
AUDIENCE: Yeah like,
6,000 years ago.

00:35:48.890 --> 00:35:50.300
What shreds we know, you know?

00:35:50.300 --> 00:35:51.580
DAVID PETERSON: I think
we do know some stuff

00:35:51.580 --> 00:35:52.750
about 6,000 years ago.

00:35:52.750 --> 00:35:55.780
But you know essentially--

00:35:55.780 --> 00:36:00.260
AUDIENCE: Hard consonants
and like how it directly

00:36:00.260 --> 00:36:02.771
translates to an object.

00:36:02.771 --> 00:36:03.810
You know phonemes.

00:36:03.810 --> 00:36:05.780
DAVID PETERSON: I
don't really buy that.

00:36:05.780 --> 00:36:08.170
I don't think that like the
earliest, earliest, earliest

00:36:08.170 --> 00:36:10.180
forms of languages--
they were necessarily

00:36:10.180 --> 00:36:14.180
like such great sound
symbolism like that.

00:36:14.180 --> 00:36:16.820
There is sound symbolism that
exists throughout the world's

00:36:16.820 --> 00:36:18.430
languages so often.

00:36:18.430 --> 00:36:21.550
If you have vowel where
your mouth is closed,

00:36:21.550 --> 00:36:23.770
like E, it's often
associated with small things,

00:36:23.770 --> 00:36:25.730
and if your mouth is
wide open, ah, it's often

00:36:25.730 --> 00:36:27.850
associated with large things.

00:36:27.850 --> 00:36:31.590
But beyond that
there's not a lot

00:36:31.590 --> 00:36:33.970
that isn't language specific.

00:36:33.970 --> 00:36:41.560
So if you think about English
we have words like glean, glint,

00:36:41.560 --> 00:36:44.486
glisten, glitter, glow.

00:36:44.486 --> 00:36:46.110
You could probably
come up with others.

00:36:46.110 --> 00:36:46.880
There are others.

00:36:46.880 --> 00:36:49.200
And you'll notice those
all kind of have something

00:36:49.200 --> 00:36:51.480
to do with shininess, right?

00:36:51.480 --> 00:36:55.020
But there's nothing--
I mean that's

00:36:55.020 --> 00:36:56.720
an English specific thing only.

00:36:56.720 --> 00:36:59.360
It has nothing to do with any
other language on the planet.

00:36:59.360 --> 00:37:04.020
There's nothing about Gla--
Glee, it means Glee-- no,

00:37:04.020 --> 00:37:06.040
there's nothing about
Gla that tells you,

00:37:06.040 --> 00:37:07.920
oh this has to do
with shininess.

00:37:07.920 --> 00:37:12.060
It's just a bizarre cultural,
historical artifact of English.

00:37:12.060 --> 00:37:13.530
Now having said
that, of course I

00:37:13.530 --> 00:37:15.720
study the history
of languages a lot.

00:37:15.720 --> 00:37:17.540
I don't think that
we're at a point,

00:37:17.540 --> 00:37:20.120
and I doubt we'll ever be at
the point, where we can say this

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:22.120
is where language was created.

00:37:22.120 --> 00:37:24.317
This is how it came to be.

00:37:24.317 --> 00:37:26.150
I don't think we're
ever going to get there.

00:37:26.150 --> 00:37:28.490
Honestly, we're pressing it
when we go back to things

00:37:28.490 --> 00:37:30.560
like Proto-Indo-European.

00:37:30.560 --> 00:37:33.530
There's a lot we know but
then there's so much we don't.

00:37:33.530 --> 00:37:36.890
There are definitely
people out there

00:37:36.890 --> 00:37:38.690
who have looked into doing this.

00:37:38.690 --> 00:37:41.930
Like Joseph Greenberg who's
a famous, famous linguist

00:37:41.930 --> 00:37:43.980
and made some
brilliant typological

00:37:43.980 --> 00:37:47.200
discoveries was a big
believer in proto world.

00:37:47.200 --> 00:37:49.910
That you could actually find
the commonalities between all

00:37:49.910 --> 00:37:51.780
the languages on the planet.

00:37:51.780 --> 00:37:56.580
I would say most linguists
don't accept that,

00:37:56.580 --> 00:38:00.124
wouldn't even except some
of the less grandiose claims

00:38:00.124 --> 00:38:02.040
like there were 10
original language families,

00:38:02.040 --> 00:38:03.320
which I've also heard.

00:38:03.320 --> 00:38:04.880
I'd say most don't accept that.

00:38:04.880 --> 00:38:08.230
Most know that the further
back in history you

00:38:08.230 --> 00:38:11.310
go the less and less certain
we can be about what we're

00:38:11.310 --> 00:38:13.124
saying about these languages.

00:38:13.124 --> 00:38:15.040
Though, but hey, from
here on out everything's

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:16.780
going to be recorded.

00:38:16.780 --> 00:38:18.170
So that's nice.

00:38:18.170 --> 00:38:19.530
AUDIENCE: Thanks for the talk.

00:38:19.530 --> 00:38:20.630
Really interesting.

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:23.330
I'm curious, do you have
any particular features

00:38:23.330 --> 00:38:25.810
of your languages, or
of languages in general,

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:28.690
that you feel are really
interesting, that you

00:38:28.690 --> 00:38:30.140
feel really enamored with?

00:38:30.140 --> 00:38:32.440
Like you mentioned
in the example

00:38:32.440 --> 00:38:35.160
that you gave you
have noun classes,

00:38:35.160 --> 00:38:38.690
you had spelling
variations, you had

00:38:38.690 --> 00:38:44.010
this very systematic writing
system-- reminds me of Hangul,

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:44.950
for instance.

00:38:44.950 --> 00:38:47.820
Is there anything that you
feel that you notice yourself

00:38:47.820 --> 00:38:52.120
saying, like I can't put
this in another language

00:38:52.120 --> 00:38:54.270
again, because I
do it all the time.

00:38:54.270 --> 00:38:57.802
DAVID PETERSON: Yeah, well
definitely noun classes

00:38:57.802 --> 00:38:59.260
are one of my most
favorite things.

00:38:59.260 --> 00:39:01.155
It's so easy to create
words, and to create

00:39:01.155 --> 00:39:02.780
really interesting
words that you never

00:39:02.780 --> 00:39:04.696
would have thought of
if you had noun classes.

00:39:04.696 --> 00:39:07.120
I love them to death.

00:39:07.120 --> 00:39:10.600
But I've only ever-- the one
I did for Irathient, that

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:14.060
was like my second big one and
I haven't done that precisely

00:39:14.060 --> 00:39:17.010
again, but I could
just do that all day.

00:39:17.010 --> 00:39:19.390
Love noun classes.

00:39:19.390 --> 00:39:21.780
Noun case is another
one I'm fond of,

00:39:21.780 --> 00:39:23.150
but that you can get away what.

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:27.250
I mean, most languages have
noun case in some form.

00:39:27.250 --> 00:39:29.970
But yeah, case systems
are loads of fun.

00:39:29.970 --> 00:39:34.340
I think where I get into
trouble is not something

00:39:34.340 --> 00:39:36.540
that I love but something
that's a weak point of me.

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:39.340
I just hate verbs.

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:44.290
It's so easy, it's so easy
to do a verb system that's

00:39:44.290 --> 00:39:46.880
basically perfect imperfect.

00:39:46.880 --> 00:39:49.730
Lots of languages
either are that way,

00:39:49.730 --> 00:39:51.580
or started out that way.

00:39:51.580 --> 00:39:53.740
Where there's just basically
a binary distinction

00:39:53.740 --> 00:39:57.240
of perfect and imperfect,
so done and not done,

00:39:57.240 --> 00:39:58.740
and it's so easy
to just do that.

00:39:58.740 --> 00:40:03.080
Say, all right we're done,
but I kind of do it too much.

00:40:03.080 --> 00:40:07.780
I know I shouldn't, but
verbs are just so complex.

00:40:07.780 --> 00:40:13.300
They change by the decade
precisely how they're used.

00:40:13.300 --> 00:40:17.980
Just watch a football
game and the guy

00:40:17.980 --> 00:40:23.220
says during the replay--
it's like he'll say,

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:25.180
if he doesn't pick up
that block right there,

00:40:25.180 --> 00:40:26.990
he doesn't run to the end zone.

00:40:26.990 --> 00:40:30.070
That's all present tense
but that's not actually

00:40:30.070 --> 00:40:30.955
the present tense.

00:40:30.955 --> 00:40:32.580
I mean it's the
present tense, but it's

00:40:32.580 --> 00:40:35.641
some sort of weird, bizarre,
hypothetical, counter-factual

00:40:35.641 --> 00:40:36.140
tense.

00:40:36.140 --> 00:40:39.540
We just use the present tense
for it in a sports context

00:40:39.540 --> 00:40:40.490
only.

00:40:40.490 --> 00:40:41.580
Right?

00:40:41.580 --> 00:40:44.860
That happens, that's
real verbs right there,

00:40:44.860 --> 00:40:48.410
and it just pisses
me straight off.

00:40:48.410 --> 00:40:50.952
That's what it's the worst part
of learning any new language.

00:40:50.952 --> 00:40:53.034
I don't care how simple a
language will tell you--

00:40:53.034 --> 00:40:55.350
it's like, oh you have
these agreement patterns.

00:40:55.350 --> 00:40:57.120
We don't have that in Chinese.

00:40:57.120 --> 00:40:58.504
Yeah, I don't care.

00:40:58.504 --> 00:40:59.920
I'm not learning
that verb system.

00:40:59.920 --> 00:41:01.750
It's incredibly complex.

00:41:01.750 --> 00:41:03.720
Just because the words
themselves don't change,

00:41:03.720 --> 00:41:05.303
doesn't mean the
system isn't complex.

00:41:05.303 --> 00:41:08.050
It probably means
it's more complex.

00:41:08.050 --> 00:41:10.300
Verbs!

00:41:10.300 --> 00:41:12.360
AUDIENCE: I'm curious
what's your favorite word?

00:41:12.360 --> 00:41:13.660
What language is it in?

00:41:13.660 --> 00:41:16.180
What does it mean, and
what was the context

00:41:16.180 --> 00:41:18.474
that you like it used in?

00:41:18.474 --> 00:41:19.640
Do you have a favorite word?

00:41:19.640 --> 00:41:21.598
DAVID PETERSON: A favorite
word that I created?

00:41:21.598 --> 00:41:23.552
AUDIENCE: Yeah, more likely.

00:41:23.552 --> 00:41:24.510
You could tell us both.

00:41:24.510 --> 00:41:26.093
The ones you like
that others created,

00:41:26.093 --> 00:41:28.190
but I'm kind of
curious about yours.

00:41:28.190 --> 00:41:30.370
DAVID PETERSON: I don't know.

00:41:30.370 --> 00:41:33.300
I actually-- it's funny,
I get this question a lot

00:41:33.300 --> 00:41:36.574
and I never have a very good
answer, and I'll tell you why.

00:41:36.574 --> 00:41:37.990
The words that I
remember the most

00:41:37.990 --> 00:41:39.364
are the ones that
I use the most,

00:41:39.364 --> 00:41:41.210
and they tend to be
very prosaic words.

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:49.060
Like the word for "need
to" in Dothraki, zigerelat.

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:51.970
I know that one but it's there's
nothing very great about it.

00:41:51.970 --> 00:41:54.790
I just use it all the time.

00:41:54.790 --> 00:41:58.460
And actually I was just
talking about this.

00:41:58.460 --> 00:42:00.220
There's a particular
reason I think

00:42:00.220 --> 00:42:01.990
that I don't remember
a lot of the really

00:42:01.990 --> 00:42:04.060
fancy, interesting words.

00:42:04.060 --> 00:42:06.870
Like I'll give you
an example of one

00:42:06.870 --> 00:42:08.860
that I know because
I used it recently.

00:42:08.860 --> 00:42:11.470
[? "Hej" ?] is the word
for "sticky" in Dothraki,

00:42:11.470 --> 00:42:17.450
and [? "hejov" ?] is a word
for a situation that is more

00:42:17.450 --> 00:42:21.370
trouble than it's worth and so
you'll likely want to avoid it.

00:42:21.370 --> 00:42:25.050
I thought that was a pretty good
word but I've never used it,

00:42:25.050 --> 00:42:27.230
and the reason is
that-- especially

00:42:27.230 --> 00:42:31.220
for these shows, the words--
I'm acting as a translator.

00:42:31.220 --> 00:42:33.210
I get English
scripts and then have

00:42:33.210 --> 00:42:37.210
to translate what's given
to me, and so the words

00:42:37.210 --> 00:42:38.670
that I end up
using are the words

00:42:38.670 --> 00:42:39.780
that the writers
come up with and they

00:42:39.780 --> 00:42:42.330
don't think of these really
fantastic and interesting words

00:42:42.330 --> 00:42:44.030
that exist in these languages.

00:42:44.030 --> 00:42:46.320
Where perhaps if there
were native speakers,

00:42:46.320 --> 00:42:47.731
they would find uses for them.

00:42:47.731 --> 00:42:49.480
They would have different
patterns of use,

00:42:49.480 --> 00:42:51.840
but instead we're working
with English patterns

00:42:51.840 --> 00:42:56.900
of usage and words that the
English speakers come up with.

00:42:56.900 --> 00:43:00.420
So consequently since my
most common interaction

00:43:00.420 --> 00:43:04.660
with my own languages
is when I translate,

00:43:04.660 --> 00:43:06.890
those words are the
ones I know the most.

00:43:06.890 --> 00:43:09.440
So there are scores of
words that I have completely

00:43:09.440 --> 00:43:12.090
forgotten about, and I
usually only run across them

00:43:12.090 --> 00:43:14.170
when I'm looking for some
word in my dictionary

00:43:14.170 --> 00:43:16.420
and it happens to be right
next to another word that's

00:43:16.420 --> 00:43:17.840
really cool, I'm
like, oh my god, I

00:43:17.840 --> 00:43:18.965
forgot I created that word!

00:43:18.965 --> 00:43:20.140
It's so cool!

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:25.630
Now, here's the word for
belt. I go on from there.

00:43:25.630 --> 00:43:27.830
I do have a least
favorite word in English.

00:43:27.830 --> 00:43:29.810
Crafts.

00:43:29.810 --> 00:43:32.510
That's the most hideous
word I've ever heard.

00:43:32.510 --> 00:43:33.852
Just awful.

00:43:33.852 --> 00:43:37.250
AUDIENCE: Do you have a
word aversion for that?

00:43:37.250 --> 00:43:39.620
DAVID PETERSON:
First of all, crafts.

00:43:39.620 --> 00:43:42.470
It's f-t-s right in a row.

00:43:42.470 --> 00:43:45.850
That's barbaric.

00:43:45.850 --> 00:43:53.030
And it just-- makes me think
of the term arts and crafts.

00:43:53.030 --> 00:43:54.595
It's just weirds me out.

00:43:57.110 --> 00:43:58.930
There was a-- who has the mic?

00:43:58.930 --> 00:44:01.800
Over there.

00:44:01.800 --> 00:44:03.780
AUDIENCE: You'd
mentioned complexity

00:44:03.780 --> 00:44:05.930
in one of the
previous questions.

00:44:05.930 --> 00:44:09.029
Are there-- in the
conlang community

00:44:09.029 --> 00:44:10.570
are there any measures
of complexity,

00:44:10.570 --> 00:44:13.407
or precision, or granularity
for different languages?

00:44:13.407 --> 00:44:15.240
DAVID PETERSON: Yes,
but they're not applied

00:44:15.240 --> 00:44:18.280
to artistic languages usually.

00:44:18.280 --> 00:44:20.140
As languages created
for the purpose of art.

00:44:20.140 --> 00:44:22.570
Usually where you see
things like that discussed

00:44:22.570 --> 00:44:24.340
are creation of
auxiliary languages.

00:44:24.340 --> 00:44:27.069
So, languages like Esperanto
that are built either

00:44:27.069 --> 00:44:29.110
for international
communication, or communication

00:44:29.110 --> 00:44:30.160
within a group.

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:34.030
They try to measure things
much more objectively so they

00:44:34.030 --> 00:44:36.700
can say which one is better.

00:44:36.700 --> 00:44:39.640
We tend not to do that
in the artistic language

00:44:39.640 --> 00:44:43.610
community for the same reason
that you don't typically

00:44:43.610 --> 00:44:45.490
go to paintings and say
which one is better,

00:44:45.490 --> 00:44:47.115
and then come up with
objective reasons

00:44:47.115 --> 00:44:50.380
for why one painting
is better than another.

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:52.390
There are certain
measures that exist

00:44:52.390 --> 00:44:57.740
within linguistics, such as
the minimum word dependency.

00:44:57.740 --> 00:44:59.700
I'm going to get this wrong.

00:44:59.700 --> 00:45:01.889
Minimal length
dependency, I think it is.

00:45:01.889 --> 00:45:04.180
There's a paper that just
came out of this-- a kid just

00:45:04.180 --> 00:45:05.840
came out of MIT on this.

00:45:05.840 --> 00:45:08.700
Where if you subscribe to
the theory of morphemes,

00:45:08.700 --> 00:45:12.610
which I don't, but if you
do, you can chop up a word

00:45:12.610 --> 00:45:16.590
and see how many of them there
are and come up with number

00:45:16.590 --> 00:45:19.160
that tells you
something or other.

00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:21.720
But I haven't used
it myself, and I

00:45:21.720 --> 00:45:23.140
don't think it
enjoys a lot of use

00:45:23.140 --> 00:45:25.450
within the artistic
language community,

00:45:25.450 --> 00:45:27.800
but definitely within the
oxlang and perhaps englang

00:45:27.800 --> 00:45:30.050
community, englang being
engineering languages

00:45:30.050 --> 00:45:32.659
that don't necessarily
need to be natural.

00:45:32.659 --> 00:45:34.200
AUDIENCE: As somebody
who had studied

00:45:34.200 --> 00:45:37.890
a lot of languages and
studies a lot of linguists,

00:45:37.890 --> 00:45:42.280
I'm sure you're aware that
there's some languages that

00:45:42.280 --> 00:45:45.950
are-- although they have
their own vocabulary,

00:45:45.950 --> 00:45:49.410
but structurally in
terms of lexemes,

00:45:49.410 --> 00:45:50.660
they're very close to English.

00:45:50.660 --> 00:45:53.780
You basically can do a
word for word translation

00:45:53.780 --> 00:45:57.260
and maybe change the
word order a little bit.

00:45:57.260 --> 00:46:01.050
There are other languages
where in that culture,

00:46:01.050 --> 00:46:05.292
in that language, you just
express an idea structurally

00:46:05.292 --> 00:46:06.250
completely differently.

00:46:09.390 --> 00:46:12.990
You can't really say in
translating one sentence

00:46:12.990 --> 00:46:15.050
to another that this
word corresponds to this,

00:46:15.050 --> 00:46:16.280
and that to that.

00:46:16.280 --> 00:46:21.280
When you do these construction
languages for TV and movies

00:46:21.280 --> 00:46:26.510
that you know you're going to
be translating English scripts,

00:46:26.510 --> 00:46:30.240
does that tend to make
you create languages

00:46:30.240 --> 00:46:32.570
that are structurally
closer to English

00:46:32.570 --> 00:46:35.700
so your translation
job will be easier?

00:46:35.700 --> 00:46:38.240
DAVID PETERSON: No, not a bit.

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:39.430
No.

00:46:39.430 --> 00:46:40.620
Not at all.

00:46:40.620 --> 00:46:43.319
But of course, just a
comment, the languages

00:46:43.319 --> 00:46:45.860
that are going to be closer to
English structurally are going

00:46:45.860 --> 00:46:48.780
to be those that are
related English genetically,

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:52.280
like in the Germanic
languages, but even so, there's

00:46:52.280 --> 00:46:54.674
a general tenant
that we pretty much

00:46:54.674 --> 00:46:56.840
believe to be true that you
could translate anything

00:46:56.840 --> 00:46:57.620
into anything.

00:46:57.620 --> 00:46:59.550
When it comes to--

00:46:59.550 --> 00:47:01.800
AUDIENCE: I'm not
saying that's not true.

00:47:01.800 --> 00:47:04.720
DAVID PETERSON: But yeah,
like the word for word.

00:47:04.720 --> 00:47:07.240
AUDIENCE: You know what
you're going to be doing

00:47:07.240 --> 00:47:08.869
and to make it
easier for yourself.

00:47:08.869 --> 00:47:10.410
DAVID PETERSON:
Yeah, no, not at all.

00:47:10.410 --> 00:47:10.910
No.

00:47:10.910 --> 00:47:14.070
Because that would be boring.

00:47:14.070 --> 00:47:17.120
The reason I do this is I
love creating languages.

00:47:17.120 --> 00:47:17.922
That's my fun.

00:47:17.922 --> 00:47:19.880
I mean the closest thing
I've gotten to English

00:47:19.880 --> 00:47:22.567
is actually Old
Trigedasleng in "The 100"

00:47:22.567 --> 00:47:24.525
but that's because it's
actually supposed to be

00:47:24.525 --> 00:47:25.780
an evolved form of English.

00:47:25.780 --> 00:47:26.860
English 100 years later.

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:28.615
So it's like it's
really-- but there it's

00:47:28.615 --> 00:47:30.990
supposed to be like English
because it's kind of supposed

00:47:30.990 --> 00:47:32.550
to be English, right.

00:47:32.550 --> 00:47:34.450
But other than that, no.

00:47:34.450 --> 00:47:37.200
Honestly, the languages
couldn't be more different.

00:47:37.200 --> 00:47:42.410
They range from marginally,
somewhat, kind of close,

00:47:42.410 --> 00:47:47.780
to totally,
unrecognizably, out there.

00:47:47.780 --> 00:47:49.610
That's how I have my fun.

00:47:49.610 --> 00:47:53.120
AUDIENCE: So every year we
lose dozens, maybe hundreds,

00:47:53.120 --> 00:47:55.030
of human languages
to extinction,

00:47:55.030 --> 00:47:57.530
and we lose the cultural
payload with them.

00:47:57.530 --> 00:48:02.340
How do you feel about the ethics
of conlangs going into-- people

00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:04.259
running around geeking
out on Klingon when

00:48:04.259 --> 00:48:06.300
we're losing real human
languages that they could

00:48:06.300 --> 00:48:07.240
be learning.

00:48:07.240 --> 00:48:11.740
And why do you not consider
using obscure human languages

00:48:11.740 --> 00:48:13.360
for some of these shows?

00:48:13.360 --> 00:48:14.800
Bring them back a little bit.

00:48:14.800 --> 00:48:15.740
Give them a new life.

00:48:15.740 --> 00:48:18.720
Make people aware
of them, rather than

00:48:18.720 --> 00:48:20.070
artificial languages.

00:48:20.070 --> 00:48:21.611
DAVID PETERSON: Let
me ask you this--

00:48:21.611 --> 00:48:23.740
how do you feel about
people getting really,

00:48:23.740 --> 00:48:26.910
really excited about novels
like "The Hunger Games," which

00:48:26.910 --> 00:48:28.840
are stories about
fake people, when

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:31.110
we're losing the stories
of real people every day

00:48:31.110 --> 00:48:32.620
that are dying?

00:48:32.620 --> 00:48:37.200
AUDIENCE: Honestly, I think
that's sort of false analogy.

00:48:37.200 --> 00:48:41.335
We have-- and I admit I come
from a very specific basis

00:48:41.335 --> 00:48:42.280
on this.

00:48:42.280 --> 00:48:43.930
But I guess I would
say, how do you

00:48:43.930 --> 00:48:45.890
feel about ISIS
destroying antiquities

00:48:45.890 --> 00:48:47.410
when we could make new stuff?

00:48:47.410 --> 00:48:47.930
DAVID PETERSON: I'm
sorry say the last part?

00:48:47.930 --> 00:48:49.825
AUDIENCE: How do you feel about
ISIS destroying antiquities

00:48:49.825 --> 00:48:51.610
when you could make new stuff?

00:48:51.610 --> 00:48:53.820
That's equivalent to yours.

00:48:53.820 --> 00:48:56.140
Is it-- and I'm not saying
what you're doing is wrong--

00:48:56.140 --> 00:48:56.910
DAVID PETERSON:
You're saying that I'm

00:48:56.910 --> 00:48:58.990
destroying natural
languages in order produce--

00:48:58.990 --> 00:49:01.531
AUDIENCE: I'm not saying you're
destroying natural languages.

00:49:01.531 --> 00:49:04.800
I'm saying, could we not
use some of the energies

00:49:04.800 --> 00:49:07.820
that people go into learning
conlanguages, geeking out

00:49:07.820 --> 00:49:10.365
about con languages, going
to Klingon conventions.

00:49:10.365 --> 00:49:13.430
I'll tell you I got very annoyed
when I see-- I saw even here

00:49:13.430 --> 00:49:15.012
at Google recently,
people talking

00:49:15.012 --> 00:49:16.470
about looking for
Klingon resources

00:49:16.470 --> 00:49:18.780
to do something in Klingon,
and it's like great,

00:49:18.780 --> 00:49:21.550
but let's put that effort
to saving a real language

00:49:21.550 --> 00:49:23.300
because when we lose
those languages, when

00:49:23.300 --> 00:49:25.890
the last speaker dies,
it's never coming back

00:49:25.890 --> 00:49:26.990
as a living language.

00:49:26.990 --> 00:49:29.780
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah
so, of course--

00:49:29.780 --> 00:49:31.390
and in fact if
they weren't going

00:49:31.390 --> 00:49:33.970
to be doing Klingon they would
be doing the other thing,

00:49:33.970 --> 00:49:35.278
right?

00:49:35.278 --> 00:49:36.490
AUDIENCE: That's how it ends.

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:37.570
MALE SPEAKER: No, of course not.

00:49:37.570 --> 00:49:37.820
So let's stop--

00:49:37.820 --> 00:49:39.700
AUDIENCE: You could use
real human languages

00:49:39.700 --> 00:49:39.970
for some of these--

00:49:39.970 --> 00:49:40.840
DAVID PETERSON: You
certainly could.

00:49:40.840 --> 00:49:41.340
Yeah.

00:49:41.340 --> 00:49:43.220
We could have found
a-- for example,

00:49:43.220 --> 00:49:46.910
we could have found some
very rarely spoken language

00:49:46.910 --> 00:49:49.530
and given it to the
barbaric, Dothraki who are

00:49:49.530 --> 00:49:51.280
ripping people's tongues out.

00:49:51.280 --> 00:49:52.932
How would that have been?

00:49:52.932 --> 00:49:54.890
AUDIENCE: I wasn't
necessarily saying Dothraki.

00:49:54.890 --> 00:49:55.681
DAVID PETERSON: OK.

00:49:55.681 --> 00:49:58.672
OK, but that's actually
the issue that comes up.

00:49:58.672 --> 00:50:00.380
For example, there
are a lot of languages

00:50:00.380 --> 00:50:01.720
that are dying out right now.

00:50:01.720 --> 00:50:05.860
Not the majority of them but
certainly a minority of them,

00:50:05.860 --> 00:50:07.970
that are dying
because the speakers

00:50:07.970 --> 00:50:11.140
don't want other people
to use their language.

00:50:11.140 --> 00:50:12.880
They don't want people
to write it down.

00:50:12.880 --> 00:50:14.840
They don't want
foreigners speaking them.

00:50:14.840 --> 00:50:16.590
Do we respect that?

00:50:16.590 --> 00:50:20.530
Or do we just kind of sigh
and let the language die out

00:50:20.530 --> 00:50:23.510
and respect the wishes of these
people who don't want contact

00:50:23.510 --> 00:50:24.910
with the outside world?

00:50:24.910 --> 00:50:27.030
It's a different kind
of ethical question.

00:50:27.030 --> 00:50:30.160
But personally there are
two ways of looking at it.

00:50:30.160 --> 00:50:33.360
One, artistically if you're
talking about a totally

00:50:33.360 --> 00:50:37.030
fictional reality it
breaks the reality

00:50:37.030 --> 00:50:39.970
to use a language that
actually is spoken

00:50:39.970 --> 00:50:41.910
by other people on Earth.

00:50:41.910 --> 00:50:44.660
It's kind of an odd thing.

00:50:44.660 --> 00:50:46.302
I always find it
odd when people are

00:50:46.302 --> 00:50:47.760
speaking English
when they oughtn't

00:50:47.760 --> 00:50:50.640
to be-- like "Amadeus."

00:50:50.640 --> 00:50:52.090
I mean it was a fantastic movie.

00:50:52.090 --> 00:50:53.965
It was a fantastic
movie, but honestly why

00:50:53.965 --> 00:50:55.090
were they speaking English?

00:50:55.090 --> 00:50:56.760
Especially like, I don't know.

00:50:56.760 --> 00:50:59.385
Well, it's actually kind of
a bizarre thing of movies

00:50:59.385 --> 00:51:01.760
that we think that British
English would have been better

00:51:01.760 --> 00:51:03.820
than American English.

00:51:03.820 --> 00:51:07.050
I mean it wouldn't, it's the
same thing, but I don't know.

00:51:07.050 --> 00:51:10.090
So artistically it
simply breaks it,

00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:13.090
and honestly there's
no alternative here.

00:51:13.090 --> 00:51:16.640
The alternative to using
creative language in "Defiance"

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:17.890
was English.

00:51:17.890 --> 00:51:19.780
They were never, ever
going to consider

00:51:19.780 --> 00:51:22.430
using any other
natural language,

00:51:22.430 --> 00:51:26.364
or the expense involved
in finding somebody

00:51:26.364 --> 00:51:27.780
to translate into
those languages.

00:51:27.780 --> 00:51:31.090
And then furthermore,
if you think about,

00:51:31.090 --> 00:51:37.410
especially some very--
some minority languages

00:51:37.410 --> 00:51:41.820
that aren't spoken very
well-- by very many people,

00:51:41.820 --> 00:51:45.110
and you start to translate some
of the dialogue in "Defiance."

00:51:45.110 --> 00:51:47.240
For example, this
sentence that I showed you

00:51:47.240 --> 00:51:49.180
about the chlorine gas.

00:51:49.180 --> 00:51:53.320
Odds are that Piraha doesn't
have a word for chlorine.

00:51:53.320 --> 00:51:56.240
So then it's a question
of what you do.

00:51:56.240 --> 00:51:59.410
It seems doubtful that you
could get a speaker up there who

00:51:59.410 --> 00:52:01.674
would have to learn and
understand English well enough

00:52:01.674 --> 00:52:04.090
and perform on a deadline to
be able to translate into it,

00:52:04.090 --> 00:52:05.640
so you need somebody else.

00:52:05.640 --> 00:52:08.967
And undoubtedly they would
have to create words.

00:52:08.967 --> 00:52:10.550
They would have to
create words either

00:52:10.550 --> 00:52:13.740
by working with
native roots, or have

00:52:13.740 --> 00:52:17.410
a whole load of English
borrowings in there, or worse,

00:52:17.410 --> 00:52:20.260
create words they kind of
look like the real language

00:52:20.260 --> 00:52:22.070
and use them in those scripts.

00:52:22.070 --> 00:52:26.300
Which to me seems
really offensive.

00:52:26.300 --> 00:52:28.860
Essentially you're
creating words

00:52:28.860 --> 00:52:32.514
to plunk down into somebody's
actually existing language.

00:52:32.514 --> 00:52:34.680
You're not a part of the
culture, and you're saying,

00:52:34.680 --> 00:52:37.860
well we're going to represent
this as a word in your language

00:52:37.860 --> 00:52:41.490
for the purposes of
this television show.

00:52:41.490 --> 00:52:45.550
I just can't see that
being a good idea.

00:52:45.550 --> 00:52:49.910
On a separate note, if you just
to kind of remove the created

00:52:49.910 --> 00:52:52.010
language aspect entirely.

00:52:52.010 --> 00:52:54.740
The fact, of course, that
there are dying languages

00:52:54.740 --> 00:52:57.840
is terrible.

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:00.820
It's a question of what
one can do as an outsider

00:53:00.820 --> 00:53:07.820
in order to either prevent it,
or to preserve those languages.

00:53:07.820 --> 00:53:11.620
I'm not sure how a lot of
speakers of minority languages

00:53:11.620 --> 00:53:15.240
would feel if there were,
say, a bunch of teenagers

00:53:15.240 --> 00:53:17.680
from Southern
California who started

00:53:17.680 --> 00:53:19.820
to learn their language
just because they thought

00:53:19.820 --> 00:53:21.380
it was cool, and
funky, and it was

00:53:21.380 --> 00:53:26.300
used for these quirky
people in this show.

00:53:26.300 --> 00:53:28.200
That, at least for
me, that would make

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:31.410
me feel a little uncomfortable.

00:53:31.410 --> 00:53:35.555
So I think that the
sentiment is well founded.

00:53:35.555 --> 00:53:37.430
I don't think that the
solution you presented

00:53:37.430 --> 00:53:43.840
is a good one, or feasible,
or necessarily respectful.

00:53:43.840 --> 00:53:49.245
I also think that for standard
preservation of languages

00:53:49.245 --> 00:53:51.120
there are people that
are trained to do that.

00:53:51.120 --> 00:53:52.659
It's not an easy thing.

00:53:52.659 --> 00:53:54.450
And of course I know
them, and in fact have

00:53:54.450 --> 00:53:57.320
studied under them coming
through linguistics.

00:53:57.320 --> 00:54:01.930
It's not just something
that anybody can do.

00:54:01.930 --> 00:54:05.490
It takes a lot of
work with the culture,

00:54:05.490 --> 00:54:08.410
and having worked with Hollywood
a bunch, it's a lot of work

00:54:08.410 --> 00:54:10.640
that I know that nobody
would be interested in doing.

00:54:10.640 --> 00:54:11.930
They wouldn't be interested
in paying for it,

00:54:11.930 --> 00:54:14.221
they wouldn't be interested
in taking the time with it,

00:54:14.221 --> 00:54:15.950
because they have
deadlines and they're

00:54:15.950 --> 00:54:18.300
doing what they're going to do.

00:54:18.300 --> 00:54:20.530
I'm not sure if that
answered every single aspect

00:54:20.530 --> 00:54:24.610
of your question but if not,
I'm happy to talk about it

00:54:24.610 --> 00:54:27.050
further because this
is an issue that

00:54:27.050 --> 00:54:30.260
comes up every
single time created

00:54:30.260 --> 00:54:31.410
languages are discussed.

00:54:31.410 --> 00:54:33.490
So thanks.

00:54:33.490 --> 00:54:35.040
[APPLAUSE]

